6. The Value Creation System & The Purpose of Software

[00:00:00]

What's going on, crafters? Khalil here, and in this video, we're going to get into the value creation system to talk about the purpose of software. Let's begin to clarify some of these questions and various prompts that we have around what software is, why we write software in the first place. Because this stuff is really important to get super clear on, so we can all be working from the same starting point.

So we're going to talk about the purpose of software, but first... Super serious question. What's the purpose of this thing right here? So some of you might think that this is to hold liquids. Maybe it's to hold hot liquids or to drink hot liquids, or maybe some other things you could advertise your business on it.

You could get your day started with this thing, with some coffee. I actually love to ask [00:01:00] my mentorship students this question because.

It's the type of question that gets you into the mindset of thinking about the forms of things and what comes together to create the forms of things. And this is all foundational as an abstraction designer. Good object oriented designers are able to detect when things are pluggable, draggable, serializable, and so on and so forth. And it's these forms that come together to create the purpose of things.

So that is a fun little exercise I like to do to think about the purpose of things. What you are ultimately going to find is that the purpose relies on the person using it. Let's talk about what that means. so what we're going to cover here are what are actors, what are roles, and how does it affect the purpose of software, what makes software valuable to users, and why we're working within something I call the value creation system.

So let's talk about actors and roles. You might have heard of this concept of actors before. You might have heard of roles before.

What's going on here [00:02:00] is just like there's people like you, me, Khalil. Khalil is the actor, it's a person. And a person can play a role. And in my life I play many different roles. I play a brother. I play a coach. I play a skateboarder, a musician. So an actor can have many different roles.

Now, why am I telling you about this? Why is this important? The reason why this is important is not only because it's such an important concept to thinking about design and thinking about the way that we design abstractions, but this is really important to understand the purpose of software. What ends up happening is The purpose of anything completely depends on the goal of the role.

For example, if there is a child, and what does a child want to do? To have fun. The child is going to see a stone and assign a purpose to the stone, and that's just for casting it into the water to make [00:03:00] ripples. Now if there's a warrior, the warrior might have an entirely different goal.

Their goal might be to provide for the tribe, might be to go out and slay the dragon. So maybe a stone to them is actually for forging weapons. It's the same object, it's the same element, but it has a different purpose. Now think about how that might apply to software, depending on who you are and the role you're playing and what your goal probably is.

If we think back to this whole idea of the mug, what is the purpose of the mug? There is no one singular purpose of the mug. The mug has a lot of different purposes, and it's going to depend on the role and their goal. For a programmer, they might want to be alert and energized for their workday, so that's going to allow them to drink coffee out of the mug.

Compare that to that of a landscaper who might just need to finish a landscaping job and maybe they don't have the tools they need. Because the mug has the [00:04:00] ability to hold matter inside of it, they could use it to scoop dirt.

A business owner can get more clients through advertising on front of the mug.

This is something that I find really fascinating and it is important. This is perhaps the deepest level of abstraction you need to think theoretically in order to begin to determine why you're going to do anything.

So I took it into a little bit of a philosophical area. But this is a tool that domain driven design practitioners, behavior driven design practitioners often use.

We always want to start from this place of getting very clear on what the purpose is. So it is not advisable to write code without clarity on at least the who, what, why, and how.

So what does this mean about the purpose of software? It means that the purpose of software is going to depend on the people who use it.

So what are the roles? The most obvious role is that of the user.

What is it exactly that they want?

This generic way to think about this person, [00:05:00] this role can be consolidated down into a simple mental model in terms of what it is they get from the app and using it. Ultimately, what's happening here is something borrowed from the business world where you go from pain to benefit or you remain in benefit over time. And when this happens, this is how we create value.

So the goal for a user is to do that. Go from pain to benefit by saving time or having time enriched. So I'll explain this.

Now, time matters a lot. As humans, this is the most valuable thing that we have.

And generally what we do in life is we sort out these basic needs of personal development.

Physiological, safety, love, esteem, self actualization. And that's what we all move towards and buy in one way, shape, or another.

In order to solve these problems, to take up some of this space, to meet these needs, it takes time to do that.

And solving a time consuming task if you can help someone with that, it is [00:06:00] incredibly valuable. I know this probably isn't rocket science, you probably know this, but it's good to call this out and make this very blatantly apparent.

Let's imagine you have to mail a package and let's say the post office closes at 4pm and you work from 9 to 5.

So you have to kind of book some time off or find some way to take a break to get your package to the post office. Now let's say on your way there you run into traffic and you make it there a little bit late and then suddenly you don't end up there in time and you can't mail your package. You say to yourself, dang, I'm going to go again tomorrow,

and you look at your calendar and actually I do not have time. So you're going to maybe go the day after that. So you try again and then eventually you make it to the post office and you mail your package. Very good.

Now that is something that takes time. Imagine that entire process took three days, maybe it even took seven days.

What's happening here is state management. We are breaking down this system of mailing a package going from package

mailed all the [00:07:00] way back to assembling your package.

And this is something that could be offloaded by humans and put into a system. If there was an app that could ping a courier or someone to come to your door and pick up your package and then just go ahead and mail that for you. This would cut down the various states in this human state management process that you would have to walk through from however many days that is to let's say 10 minutes on the front end by just assembling the package and then two minutes to look at the notification to see that the package was mailed.

That's incredible. So do not discount the power you have my friend as a software developer. It is some serious magical stuff.

And the other aspect here is that life can be tough sometimes, so why don't we make it enjoyable? So I have here just a barrage of some memes and entertainment stuff. Right?

Because we can also enrich time. This is the other element. There is giving back time and there is enriching time.

So those two things really come together to create this interesting aspect [00:08:00] of human state management. We are either giving back time or enriching time and we are trying to move people from pain to benefit.

And if we really think about it, this is why we buy anything.

For example I have a friend who bought some socks with some lobsters on it because he really likes lobsters. There you go.

This is what I mean when I refer to the aspect of software as value or software artifacts of value. It's a thing of value you're creating.

So in essence here, something is valuable when it creates the following human state changes over time.

You can help someone go from pain to benefit or remain in benefit. And time given back and time enriched is the goal for users. Just to drive that home one more time.

And all of this comes together to create something called the value creation system. And this is a mental model that I've thought through, in terms of being able to decompose the work that we need to do.

Where at the high level we have theoretical work and at the low level we have physical work and at the very end of this we have a software artifact of value that is [00:09:00] out of the system and in the hands of a user. We're going to go into this in particular in more detail coming up and throughout the rest of the course.

So don't worry if it doesn't make that much sense just yet. We will walk through this value creation system. We'll walk through this idea of the guess points.

So let's go over what we covered here.

We learned that humans play roles in their lives, and it's these roles and the goals that are going to determine the purpose of things. The purpose of software for users is to get back time or to have time enriched. If we can do that effectively with the things that we build, we are creating software artifacts of value.

And that is very cool.

Now there are some other key roles that we need to discuss as well. There's two other ones and what makes software really dang hard is what happens when they all play together. What happens when we have multiple roles and each of those roles have different goals? That's the question. [00:10:00] So we're going to get into in the next video.
